Respiratory viral infections are of global public health concern because they are the most common cause of symptomatic disease leading to a heavy economic burden due to an increased number of sick days (
 Borchardt and Rolston, 2012; 
 Kim et al., 2017). In addition, respiratory diseases are one of the most common causes of mortality in developing countries (
 Ferkol and Schraufnagel, 2014). Among the two leading causes of respiratory virus infection are influenza (A and B) viruses and the respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) (
 Amarelle et al., 2017; 
 Heylen et al., 2017; 
 Yip et al., 2018). Most cases are observed in infants and children although the elderly and the immunocompromised are also at high risk of getting infected and develop severe disease (
 Jorquera and Tripp, 2017).
